Penetration Testing Phases

1. Reconnaissance

Passive Recon(no direct contact with target)

WHOIS lookup       → whois domain.com
DNS enumeration    → nslookup, dig, dnsrecon
Google Dorking     → site:target.com filetype:pdf
Shodan             → shodan.io — exposed services
theHarvester       → emails, subdomains, IPs

Active Recon (direct interaction)

Nmap               → port/service scanning
Nikto              → web vulnerability scanner
Gobuster/Dirb      → directory/file brute force

2. Scanning & Enumeration

Port scan
nmap -sV -sC -p- <IP>

 Web directory brute force
gobuster dir -u http://<IP> -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt

SMB Enumeration
enum4linux -a <IP>
smbclient -L //<IP>/ -N


3. Exploitation

Metasploit
msfconsole
search <vulnerability>
use exploit/...
set RHOSTS <target>
set LHOST <your_ip>
run

Manual exploitation
searchsploit <service version>

4. Post-Exploitation

Linux privilege escalation checks
id
sudo -l
find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null   (SUID files)
crontab -l
cat /etc/crontab

5. Reporting
- Document every step
- Screenshots of flags/evidence
- CVSS score vulnerabilities
- Remediation recommendations

 Common Vulnerabilities

| Vulnerability | Description |

| SQL Injection | Malicious SQL in input fields |
| XSS | Injecting scripts into web pages |
| LFI/RFI | Reading/including files on server |
| IDOR | Accessing objects by manipulating IDs |
| Command Injection | Injecting OS commands |
| Buffer Overflow | Overwriting memory beyond bounds |
